Concurrent Collections

Interview Questions:

1. What are Concurrent Collections in Java?
-->Answer:
      
      Concurrent Collections are thread-safe collection classes provided in the java.util.concurrent package.
      They are designed for multi-threaded environments.
      Unlike synchronized collections, they allow multiple threads to access the collection efficiently with better performance.
      They reduce contention by using advanced locking techniques or lock-free algorithms.
      
      Common Concurrent Collections:
      
            ConcurrentHashMap
            CopyOnWriteArrayList
            ConcurrentLinkedQueue
            ConcurrentLinkedDeque
            BlockingQueue
            ConcurrentSkipListMap
            ConcurrentSkipListSet


            
2. Why do we need concurrent collections when we already have synchronized collections?
-->Answer:

      Synchronized collections (Vector, Hashtable, Collections.synchronizedList()) lock the entire collection, allowing only one thread to access it at a time.
      
      Concurrent collections:
      
      Allow multiple threads to read simultaneously.
      Lock only the required portion (or use lock-free techniques).
      Provide much better performance in multi-threaded applications.
      
| Synchronized Collections     | Concurrent Collections           |
| ---------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Entire collection is locked  | Fine-grained locking / Lock-free |
| Lower performance            | Better performance               |
| Less scalable                | Highly scalable                  |
| Suitable for low concurrency | Suitable for high concurrency    |


      
3. What is the difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap?
-->
| Feature         | HashMap                              | ConcurrentHashMap                         |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------- |
| Thread-safe     | ❌ No                                 | ✅ Yes                                     |
| Synchronization | None                                 | Fine-grained locking (Java 8+)            |
| Performance     | Fast in single-threaded applications | Optimized for multi-threaded applications |
| Null Keys       | One allowed                          | Not allowed                               |
| Null Values     | Multiple allowed                     | Not allowed                               |
| Package         | `java.util`                          | `java.util.concurrent`                    |


ConcurrentHashMap<Integer, String> map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

map.put(1, "Java");
map.put(2, "Python");



4. What is the difference between Collections.synchronizedMap() and ConcurrentHashMap?
-->
| Feature     | synchronizedMap()         | ConcurrentHashMap          |
| ----------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Locking     | Entire map                | Fine-grained locking       |
| Performance | Lower                     | Higher                     |
| Iterator    | Must synchronize manually | Weakly consistent iterator |
| Null Keys   | Depends on underlying map | Not allowed                |
| Null Values | Depends on underlying map | Not allowed                |

Example:

Map<Integer, String> map = Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap<>());
ConcurrentHashMap<Integer, String> map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

Interview Tip:
Prefer ConcurrentHashMap for multi-threaded applications because it provides better scalability and performance.



5. What is the use of CopyOnWriteArrayList in Java?
-->Answer:

      CopyOnWriteArrayList is a thread-safe implementation of List.
      It belongs to the java.util.concurrent package.
      Whenever an element is added, updated, or removed, a new copy of the underlying array is created.
      Read operations do not require locking and are very fast.
      
      Example:
      
      CopyOnWriteArrayList<String> list = new CopyOnWriteArrayList<>();
      
      list.add("Java");
      list.add("Python");
      
      System.out.println(list);



6. When should we prefer CopyOnWriteArrayList over ArrayList?
-->Answer:
      
      Use CopyOnWriteArrayList when:
      
      Read operations are much more frequent than write operations.
      Multiple threads access the list concurrently.
      Iteration should not throw ConcurrentModificationException.
      
      Use ArrayList when:
      
      The application is single-threaded.
      Write operations (add/remove/update) are frequent.
      Maximum performance and low memory usage are required.

| Feature                         | ArrayList | CopyOnWriteArrayList       |
| ------------------------------- | --------- | -------------------------- |
| Thread-safe                     | ❌ No      | ✅ Yes                      |
| Read Performance                | Fast      | Very Fast                  |
| Write Performance               | Fast      | Slower (creates new array) |
| ConcurrentModificationException | Yes       | No                         |




7. How does CopyOnWriteArrayList achieve thread-safety internally?
-->Answer:

      CopyOnWriteArrayList achieves thread safety by using the Copy-On-Write mechanism.
            
            Working:
                  Read operations access the existing array without locking.
                  When a write operation (add(), remove(), set()) occurs:
                  A new copy of the array is created.
                  The modification is applied to the new array.
                  The reference is updated to point to the new array.
                  Existing readers continue using the old array until they finish.
                        Example:
                        
                              Initial array:
                              
                                    [Java, Python]
                              
                              After:
                              
                                    list.add("Spring");
                                    
                                    A new array is created:
                                    
                                    Old Array → [Java, Python]
                                    
                                    New Array → [Java, Python, Spring]
                                    
                                    Then the reference is switched to the new array.
                              
                              Advantages :
                                    No ConcurrentModificationException.
                                    Excellent for read-heavy applications.
                                    Safe iteration without synchronization.
                              
                              Disadvantages :
                                    Higher memory usage due to array copying.
                                    Slower write operations.



Interview Tips:
      Concurrent Collections are located in the java.util.concurrent package.
      ConcurrentHashMap is the preferred thread-safe alternative to HashMap.
      ConcurrentHashMap does not allow null keys or null values.
      CopyOnWriteArrayList is ideal for read-heavy and write-light scenarios.
      Concurrent Collections provide better scalability and performance than synchronized collections in multi-threaded environments.
